SIMPLE: shoot
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shoot
<hw>Shoot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>chute</ets>. See <er>Chute</er>. Confused with <ets>shoot</ets> to let fly.]</ety> <def>An inclined plane, either artificial or natural, down which timber, coal, etc., are caused to slide; also, a narrow passage, either natural or artificial, in a stream, where the water rushes rapidly; esp., a channel, having a swift current, connecting the ends of a bend in the stream, so as to shorten the course.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>chute</asp>, and <asp>shute</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To take a shoot</b></col>, <cd>to pass through a shoot instead of the main channel; to take the most direct course.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shoot
<hw>Shoot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Shot</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Shooting</conjf>. The old participle <conjf>Shotten</conjf> is obsolete. See <er>Shotten</er>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shotien</ets>, <ets>schotien</ets>, AS. <ets>scotian</ets>, v. i., <ets>sce⟦oacute⟧tan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>schieten</ets>, G. <ets>schie<?/en</ets>, OHG. <ets>sciozan</ets>, Icel. <ets>skj<?/ta</ets>, Sw. <ets>skjuta</ets>, Dan. <ets>skyde</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>skund</ets> to jump. ⟦root⟧159.  Cf. <er>Scot</er> a contribution, <er>Scout</er> to reject, <er>Scud</er>, <er>Scuttle</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, <er>Shot</er>, <er>Sheet</er>, <er>Shut</er>, <er>Shuttle</er>, <er>Skittish</er>, <er>Skittles</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To let fly, or cause to be driven, with force, as an arrow or a bullet; -- followed by a word denoting the missile, as an object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you please⟦br⟧
To shoot an arrow that self way.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To discharge, causing a missile to be driven forth; -- followed by a word denoting the weapon or instrument, as an object; -- often with <xex>off</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>shoot</ex> a gun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The two ends od a bow, <qex>shot</qex> off, fly from one another.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To strike with anything shot; to hit with a missile; often, to kill or wound with a firearm; -- followed by a word denoting the person or thing hit, as an object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Roger <qex>shot</qex> the hawk hovering over his master's dove house.</q> <rj><qau>A. Tucker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To send out or forth, especially with a rapid or sudden motion; to cast with the hand; to hurl; to discharge; to emit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An honest weaver as ever <qex>shot</qex> shuttle.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pit into which the dead carts had nightly <qex>shot</qex> corpses by scores.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To push or thrust forward; to project; to protrude; -- often with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, a plant <ex>shoots</ex> out a bud</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>shoot</qex> out the lip, they shake the head.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beware the secret snake that <qex>shoots</qex> a sting.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>To plane straight; to fit by planing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two pieces of wood that are <qex>shot</qex>, that is, planed or else pared with a paring chisel.</q> <rj><qau>Moxon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To pass rapidly through, over, or under; <as>as, to <ex>shoot</ex> a rapid or a bridge; to <ex>shoot</ex> a sand bar.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She . . . <qex>shoots</qex> the Stygian sound.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To variegate as if by sprinkling or intermingling; to color in spots or patches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tangled water courses slept,⟦br⟧
<qex>Shot</qex> over with purple, and green, and yellow.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be shot of</b></col>, <cd>to be discharged, cleared, or rid of.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Are you not glad <xex>to be shot of</xex> him?⟦rdquo⟧</cs>
 <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shoot
<hw>Shoot</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause an engine or weapon to discharge a missile; -- said of a person or an agent; <as>as, they <ex>shot</ex> at a target; he <ex>shoots</ex> better than he rides</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The archers have . . . <qex>shot</qex> at him.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xlix. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To discharge a missile; -- said of an engine or instrument; <as>as, the gun <ex>shoots</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be shot or propelled forcibly; -- said of a missile; to be emitted or driven; to move or extend swiftly, as if propelled; <as>as, a <ex>shooting</ex> star</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There <qex>shot</qex> a streaming lamp along the sky.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To penetrate, as a missile; to dart with a piercing sensation; <as>as, <ex>shooting</ex> pains</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy words <qex>shoot</qex> through my heart.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To feel a quick, darting pain; to throb in pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These preachers make⟦br⟧
His head to <qex>shoot</qex> and ache.</q> <rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To germinate; to bud; to sprout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Onions, as they hang, will <qex>shoot</qex> forth.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But the wild olive <qex>shoots</qex>, and shades the ungrateful plain.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To grow; to advance; <as>as, to <ex>shoot</ex> up rapidly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well <qex>shot</qex> in years he seemed.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Delightful task! to rear the tender thought,⟦br⟧
To teach the young idea how to <qex>shoot</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To change form suddenly; especially, to solidify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the menstruum be overcharged, metals will <qex>shoot</qex> into crystals.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To protrude; to jut; to project; to extend; <as>as, the land <ex>shoots</ex> into a promontory</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There <qex>shot</qex> up against the dark sky, tall, gaunt, straggling houses.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To move ahead by force of momentum, as a sailing vessel when the helm is put hard alee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shoot ahead</b></col>, <cd>to pass or move quickly forward; to outstrip others.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shoot
<hw>Shoot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of shooting; the discharge of a missile; a shot; <as>as, the <ex>shoot</ex> of a shuttle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Turkish bow giveth a very forcible <qex>shoot</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One underneath his horse to get a <qex>shoot</qex> doth stalk.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young branch or growth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Superfluous branches and <qex>shoots</qex> of this second spring.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A rush of water; a rapid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A vein of ore running in the same general direction as the lode.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>A weft thread shot through the shed by the shuttle; a pick.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <ety>[Perh. a different word.]</ety> <def>A shoat; a young hog.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shooter</ent>⟦br⟧
